{"title": "Bipolar Disorder", "source": "http://www.mentalhealthamerica.net/conditions/bipolar-disorder", "contents": [{"tag": "h3", "content": "En Espanol:"}, {"tag": "ul", "content": "\nTrastorno Bipolar: Lo Que Usted Necesita Saber\n"}, {"tag": "h3", "content": "Clinical Trials:"}, {"tag": "ul", "content": "\nNational Institute of Mental Health Clinical Trials\n"}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "What is Bipolar Disorder?"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Bipolar disorder is a mental health disorder characterized by extreme highs and lows in mood and energy. While everyone experiences ups and downs, the severe shifts that happen in bipolar disorder can have a serious impact on a person\u2019s life. More than 3.3 million American adults (1.7%) suffer from bipolar disorder in a given year. [1]\u00a0An estimated 4.4% of U.S. adults experience bipolar disorder at some time in their lives. [2]"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Contrary to how it is sometimes used in conversation, a diagnosis of bipolar disorder does not mean a person is highly emotional but rather refers to someone who experiences extended periods of mood and energy that are excessively high and or/irritable to sad and hopeless, with periods of normal mood in between."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "It typically begins in adolescence or early adulthood and continues throughout life. It is often not recognized as an illness and people who have it may suffer needlessly for years."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Bipolar disorder can be extremely distressing and disruptive for those who have this disease, their spouses, family members, friends, and employers. Although there is no known cure, bipolar disorder is treatable, and recovery is possible. Individuals with bipolar disorder can and do have successful relationships and meaningful jobs. The combination of medication, therapy, healthy lifestyle, and support helps the vast majority of people return to productive, fulfilling lives."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "\u201cBipolar disorder is treatable, and recovery is possible.\u201d"}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "What Causes Bipolar Disorder?"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Although a specific genetic link to bipolar disorder has not been pin pointed, research shows that bipolar disorder tends to run in families."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "People may inherit a tendency to develop the illness, which can then be triggered by environmental factors such as distressing life events."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Brain development, structure and chemicals called neurotransmitters, which act as messengers between nerve cells, are also thought to play a role in the development of bipolar disorder.[3]"}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "What are the Symptoms of Bipolar Disorder?"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Bipolar disorder is often difficult to recognize and diagnose. It causes a person to have a high level of energy, unrealistically expansive thoughts or ideas, and impulsive or reckless behavior. These symptoms may feel good to a person, which may lead to denial that there is a problem."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Another reason bipolar disorder is difficult to diagnose is that its symptoms may appear to be part of another illness or attributed to other problems such as substance abuse, poor school performance, or trouble in the workplace."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Symptoms of bipolar disorder fall into two categories: mania and depression."}, {"tag": "table", "content": "\n\n\n\nMania\nThe symptoms of mania, which can last up to three months if untreated include:\n\n\nDepression\nAn episode of depression can come before or after a manic, hypomanic, or normal period of mood. Symptoms include:\n\n\n\n\n\nExcessive energy, activity, restlessness, racing thoughts and rapid talking (also called \"pressured speech\").\nExtreme \u201chigh\u201d or euphoric feelings\u2014a person may feel \u201con top of the world\u201d and even\u00a0bad news or tragic events, can't change this.\nBeing easily irritated or distracted.\nDecreased need for sleep\u2014an individual may go days with little or no sleep without feeling tired.\nUnrealistic beliefs in one\u2019s ability and powers\u2014a person may experience feelings of exaggerated self-confidence or unwarranted optimism. This can lead to over ambitious work plans and the belief that nothing can stop him or her from accomplishing any task.\nUncharacteristically poor judgment\u2014a person may make poor decisions which may lead to unrealistic involvement in activities, meetings and deadlines, reckless driving, spending sprees, and/or foolish business ventures.\nUnusual sex drive or abuse of drugs\u00a0(particularly cocaine, alcohol or sleeping medications).\nProvocative, intrusive, or aggressive behavior\u2014a person may become enraged or paranoid if his or her grand ideas are stopped, or extreme\u00a0social plans are refused.\nSigns of psychosis (learn more about psychosis here)\n\n\n\n\nPersistent sad, anxious or empty mood.\nChanges in sleep such as,\u00a0getting\u00a0too much or too little, or waking in the middle-of-the-night or unusually early in the morning\u00a0\nReduced appetite and weight loss, or increased appetite accompanied by weight gain.\nIrritability or restlessness\nDifficulty concentrating, remembering or making decisions. These\u00a0may often\u00a0impact a person's ability to fulfill work,\u00a0school or other life\u00a0obligations.\nFatigue or loss of energy.\nPersistent physical symptoms that don't respond to treatment, such as chronic pain or digestive issues (like upset stomach or diarrhea).\nFeeling guilty, hopeless or worthless.\nThoughts of death or suicide, including suicide attempts.\n\n\n\n\n"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "If you or someone you know is in crisis, call 1-800-273-TALK (8255), visit your local emergency room or call 911."}, {"tag": "h2", "content": ""}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "What is the Difference Between Mania and Hypomania? [4]"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Mania is when a person has:"}, {"tag": "ul", "content": "\nat least 3 of the symptoms listed above for mania\u00a0that last for at least one week, and\nserious\u00a0impairment in work or school functioning or in usual social activities\u00a0or relationships with others, or\nsymptoms severe enough to require\u00a0hospitalization to prevent a person from hurting their\u00a0self or others, or\npsychotic features.\u00a0\n"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Hypomania is when a person has:"}, {"tag": "ul", "content": "\nat least 3 of\u00a0the symptoms listed above for mania that last at least 4 days, and\na change in their ability to function that is not typical of that person when they aren't showing symptoms,\nchanges in mood and ability to function that are noticeable by others,\nsymptoms that are not\u00a0severe enough to cause serious\u00a0impairment in social or work/school functioning, or to necessitate\u00a0hospitalization, and\nno psychotic features.\u00a0\u00a0\n"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "In summary, hypomania is a less severe and more brief form of mania.\u00a0"}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "Diagnoses and Other Terms Associated with Bipolar Disorder"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Bipolar I Disorder: Bipolar I Disorder is given when a person has at least one episode of mania. While a person with Bipolar I might only experience manic episodes, it often includes episodes of depression and hypomania. Hypomania includes the same symptoms of mania but can be shorter in duration and less severe. They do not include symptoms of psychosis or require hospitalization."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Bipolar II Disorder: Bipolar II Disorder includes at least one major depressive episode and at least one hypomanic episode. Individuals with bipolar II also tend to have longer periods of depression than people with bipolar I."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Cyclothymic Disorder: Sometimes called cyclothymia, this disorder includes episodes of hypomania and depressive symptoms that occur on a fairly regular basis. While changes in mood are not as extreme as those associated with Bipolar I and Bipolar II Disorders, it can still cause serious problems in a person\u2019s life and may later progress to symptoms of mania, hypomania, and depression."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Rapid Cycling: Rapid cycling is a term used when an individual experiences four or more episodes of hypomania, mania, or depression within a 12-month time period."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Mixed Episode: A mixed episode occurs when a person is experiencing symptoms of both depression and mania or hypomania at the same time. Individuals with bipolar disorders are at an increased risk for suicide, and this risk is thought to be especially high during mixed episodes."}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "What are the Treatments for Bipolar Disorders?"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "A combination of medication, therapy, lifestyle changes, and support from family, friends and peers help individuals with bipolar disorder to stabilize their mood and to live the lives they want.\u00a0Finding the treatment plan that works best for a person is critical for recovery.\u00a0"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Medication: Common medications used in treating bipolar disorder are lithium, anticonvulsants, and mood stabilizers. Other medications used include antipsychotics, benzodiazepines, and beta-blockers. As with all medications, medications used to treat bipolar disorder can have mild to serious side effects so it is important to talk with your doctors about how you are feeling.\u00a0\n\tLearn more about\u00a0medications."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Therapy: Both group and individual therapy can be helpful in bipolar disorder. Common types of therapy used are Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT), Dialectical Behavior Therapy (DBT), and family-focused therapies.\u00a0\n\tLearn more about\u00a0therapy."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Lifestyle changes: Healthy lifestyles changes can be an important part of overall recovery. This includes: sticking to a regular sleep schedule; reducing consumption of alcohol, caffeine, and similar substances; and exercising regularly. Some may use meditation, mind-body practices, and spirituality as resources as well.\u00a0\n\tLearn more about living a healthy lifestyle."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Support: Support and self-help groups are invaluable resources for learning coping skills, feeling accepted, and avoiding social isolation. In addition to in-person support groups and drop-in centers, there are many online communities where individuals can also find support. Additional support can be provided through employment, housing, and psychosocial rehabilitation programs.\n\tLearn more about recovery and support."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Friends and family can also join support groups to better understand how to offer encouragement and support their loved ones.\n\tLearn more about what you can do to support someone close to you."}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "From our Partners:"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Read stories from people living with Bipolar Disorder on The Mighty."}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Get additional information about Bipolar Disorder at Psych Central."}, {"tag": "h2", "content": "Other Resources:"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "National Suicide Prevention Lifeline\n\t1-800-273-TALK (8255)\nhttp://www.suicidepreventionlifeline.org"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Ryan Licht Sang Bipolar Foundation\nwww.ryanlichtsangbipolarfoundation.org"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Juvenile Bipolar Research Foundation\n\t914-468-1297\nwww.jbrf.org"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Depression and Bipolar Support Alliance (DBSA)\n\t1-800-826-3632\nwww.dbsalliance.org"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "Sources"}, {"tag": "p", "content": "[1]\u00a0Kessler, R. C., Petukhova, M., Sampson, N. A., Zaslavsky, A. M., & Wittchen, H.U. (2012). Twelve-month and lifetime prevalence and lifetime morbid risk of anxiety and mood disorders in the United States. International Journal of Methods in Psychiatric Research, 21(3), 169\u201